3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"dYdX calculates funding rates every hour using a time-weighted average price between the perpetual contract and underlying UNI spot price. The Cosmos-based v4 protocol executes funding payments automatically through smart contracts, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to 0.01% per hour. Long positions pay funding to shorts when rates are positive, reflecting market sentiment toward UNI's governance value and DeFi ecosystem growth."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","UNI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"UNI/USDT presents compelling arbitrage potential due to UNI's role as a major DeFi governance token with predictable volatility patterns around protocol upgrades and fee switch discussions. The hourly funding frequency on dYdX allows for more granular arbitrage strategies compared to 8-hour intervals on centralized exchanges."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"UNI funding rates on dYdX have historically spiked during major Uniswap governance proposals and v4 development milestones, often reaching 0.05-0.1% per hour during high volatility periods. The token shows seasonal patterns with elevated funding during DeFi summer periods and protocol fee discussions. Post-migration to Cosmos appchain, funding rates have stabilized with tighter spreads due to improved oracle accuracy and reduced MEV exploitation."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The 1-hour funding cycle creates frequent arbitrage windows, particularly when UNI experiences governance-driven price movements that lag in perpetual pricing. Cross-DEX arbitrage between dYdX and centralized exchanges like Binance becomes profitable when funding rate differentials exceed 0.02% hourly. Market makers can exploit the predictable funding spikes around Uniswap governance votes by pre-positioning before proposal announcements."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"UNI's governance token nature introduces unique risks including proposal-driven volatility that can quickly invalidate funding arbitrage positions. The Cosmos appchain migration created temporary liquidity fragmentation, occasionally causing wider bid-ask spreads during funding calculations. Smart contract risks specific to dYdX v4's new architecture require careful position sizing, and UNI's correlation with broader DeFi performance can amplify funding rate volatility during sector-wide moves."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does UNI's governance cycle affect dYdX funding rates?","answer":"UNI funding rates typically increase 24-48 hours before major governance votes as traders position for potential price movements. The hourly funding on dYdX captures these micro-movements more effectively than 8-hour cycles, creating profitable arbitrage windows for informed traders."},{"question":"What makes dYdX v4 different for UNI perpetual trading?","answer":"The Cosmos appchain provides native cross-margin capabilities and reduced gas costs for UNI positions. However, the migration initially reduced UNI trading volume, making funding rates more sensitive to large position changes compared to the previous StarkEx version."},{"question":"How do I calculate optimal position size for UNI funding arbitrage?","answer":"Consider UNI's average daily volatility (typically 3-5%) and dYdX's 10-20x leverage limits. Position sizing should account for potential 10-20% daily moves during governance events, with funding arbitrage generally profitable above 0.01% hourly rate differentials."},{"question":"What are the key UNI events that impact funding rates?","answer":"Major drivers include Uniswap governance proposals, fee switch implementations, v4 launch updates, and broader DeFi regulatory developments. These events can push funding rates to extremes of ±0.1% hourly, creating significant arbitrage opportunities for prepared traders."}]}]
